Phase 6: Live Internet Access (Web Scraping)
    What we did:

        We built a digital web browser for our AI.

        We gave the AI the ability to bypass website security and read Wikipedia.

        We extracted pure English text from the website to feed back into the AI's brain.

    How we did it:

        We updated our System Prompt to give the AI two JSON tools to choose from (get_weather and scrape_wikipedia).

        We wrote Python code to clean up the user's search words (replacing spaces with underscores)
        so the web links wouldn't break.

        We used a "Rule Override" prompt to tell the AI to stop acting like a JSON robot
        and speak normally once it found the data.

    The Purpose:

        To fix the AI's "Knowledge Cutoff" (an AI normally doesn't know anything about recent events).

        To make the AI fully autonomous so it realizes when it doesn't know an answer and
        proactively searches the live internet itself.

    Tools Used: requests library, BeautifulSoup, and Python String Slicing.

    Tool Usages & Examples:

        requests.get(url, headers): This is how our code knocks on a website's door to ask for data.

            Hard Concept Example: Websites use security bots to block automated code. We used "headers" as a
                                  fake ID badge. It tricked Wikipedia into thinking we were a human using Google Chrome.

        BeautifulSoup: A library that cleans up messy web code.

            Hard Concept Example: A raw website is full of ugly code, buttons, and ads. BeautifulSoup acts like a strainer,
                                  filtering out the junk so we only keep the <p> (paragraph) tags containing the real article.

        massive_string[:2000] (String Slicing): A way to chop up text.

            Hard Concept Example: An AI has a maximum reading limit (Context Window). If we force it to read a 10,000-word
                                  Wikipedia page, it will crash. We slice the text to only send the first 2,000 characters.

Phase 7: Streamlit Porting & Shadow Memory Architecture

    What we did:

        We moved our entire project from Gradio to Streamlit to make it look like a professional enterprise app.

        We invented a "Shadow Memory" system.

        We successfully hid our messy backend code (like database prompts and JSON tool commands) from the user's screen.

    How we did it:

        We split our memory into two levels. We kept the main memory completely clean
        (only showing what the user typed and what the AI finally answered).

        We created a hidden, temporary copy of the memory (temp_memory) for the AI to use as scratchpad.

        We injected our messy database documents and tool commands into the hidden copy,
        let the AI do its thinking there, and only sent the final, clean answer to the main screen.

    The Purpose:

        To prevent "UI Pollution" (where ugly backend code accidentally leaks onto the screen).

        To completely separate "What the User Sees" from "What the AI Thinks."

    Tools Used: Streamlit Session State, Python List Copying (.copy()), and Regular Expressions (re).

    Tool Usages & Examples:

        st.session_state: Streamlit's native memory storage.

            Hard Concept Example: Streamlit is unique because every time you press a button, it restarts your entire
                                  Python file. st.session_state is like a "Save Game" file. It protects our chat history
                                  from being deleted every time the screen refreshes.

        my_list.copy(): A tool to duplicate data.

            Hard Concept Example: In Python, if you modify a list, it permanently changes the original file.
                                  Using .copy() is like making a photocopy. We can scribble our messy code all over
                                  the photocopy (temp_memory) without ruining the original, clean document (st.session_state).

        Regular Expressions (re.search): A highly advanced text-matching tool.

            Hard Concept Example: Sometimes the AI buries its tool request inside a massive paragraph.
                                  Regex is like a search-and-rescue dog. It sniffs through thousands of words,
                                  ignoring regular English, to dig up the exact {JSON} command we need.

The Framework Comparison
    Because we built this exact same AI agent in two different visual frameworks, here is how we compare them:

    Gradio (The Quick Prototyper):

        How it works: It acts like an automatic loop. We write one single function, and Gradio handles all the UI work for us.

        The Good: It is incredibly fast and easy to set up. It automatically manages memory for us.

        The Bad: It is very hard to make it look like a highly customized, professional website.
                 It also stores memory in a strange format, forcing us to write extra code to translate it so the AI can understand it.

    Streamlit (The Production Engine):

        How it works: It redraws the entire website from top to bottom every single time the user interacts with it.

        The Good: It looks amazing out of the box. We can easily add sidebars, loading spinners, and custom colors.
                  Because we build the memory manually, we can format it perfectly for the AI without needing any translation code.

        The Bad: Because it constantly redraws the screen, any messy backend logic will accidentally show up on the user's screen.
                 It requires us to build advanced architectures (like Shadow Memory) to keep it running smoothly.

The Master Pipeline (Connecting Everything)

    Here is the grand, final picture of how data flows through the entire enterprise system we built.
    This connects our UI, our databases, the internet, and the AI into one massive pipeline:

    System Start: Our Streamlit app turns on. It wakes up our Vector Database (ChromaDB) and loads
                  our strict AI rules (JSON schemas and anti-apology rules) into the "Save Game" memory.

    User Input: The user types a question (e.g., "Who won the Super Bowl in 2024?"). We save this clean
                text and draw it beautifully on the screen.

    The Shadow Clone (Phase 7): We make a photocopy (temp_memory) of the conversation so we don't mess up the clean screen.

    RAG Database Search (Phase 5): We secretly convert the user's question into math, search our private
                                   company database for matching documents, and inject those facts into our photocopy.

    The Brain Link (Phase 3): We send the messy photocopy across the internet to the Groq AI Brain.

    The Interceptor (Phase 4): The AI reads the photocopy, realizes it doesn't know about 2024, and outputs a JSON command
                               asking to use Wikipedia. Our Regex "search dog" catches the command before the user can see it.

    Web Scraping (Phase 6): Our Python script acts like a human browser. It sneaks past Wikipedia's security,
                            finds the Super Bowl page, filters out the ads, and grabs the pure text.

    The Rule Override: We inject the Wikipedia text into our photocopy, along with a firm instruction to the AI:
                       "Read this fact, answer naturally, and do not talk about your rules."

    The Final Output: The AI reads the live Wikipedia data and generates a perfect English sentence ("The Kansas City Chiefs won").
                      We pull this clean sentence out of the photocopy, save it to the real memory, and display it on the user's screen.